@twalpole we had intended to release 2.0 at some point and drop support for Qt 4.8, but had no intentions of requiring a certain Qt 5 version. Unfortunately, I think a number of users are still on Qt 5.2 (Ubuntu trusty). Debian jessie provides 5.3, and to get 5.4, Ubuntu wily is required. 5.5 is only available in Ubuntu xenial, and Debian unstable includes 5.6 (which no longer includes the QtWebKit module).

Then there are the official binary releases from the Qt Project, which we've always recommended to our users. Unfortunately, most folks don't bother using these packages.

Based on the above, I have the feeling a version lock to 5.5 would be more trouble than it's worth.

