Yep, Capybara::Selenium::Node uses tag_name in an ifelse which makes it do many over-the-wire requests.  I added memoization and it sped things up by 27%.  Here's my local patch:

require 'capybara/selenium/node'

class Capybara::Selenium::Node
  def [](name)
    @attrs ||= {}
    @attrs[name] ||= native.attribute(name.to_s)
  rescue Selenium::WebDriver::Error::WebDriverError
    nil
  end

  def tag_name
    @tag_name ||= native.tag_name.downcase
  end
end

Yep, Capybara::Selenium::Node uses tag_name in an ifelse which makes it do many over-the-wire requests.  I added memoization and it sped things up by 27%.  Here's my local patch:

require 'capybara/selenium/node'

class Capybara::Selenium::Node
  def [](name)
    @attrs ||= {}
    @attrs[name] ||= native.attribute(name.to_s)
  rescue Selenium::WebDriver::Error::WebDriverError
    nil
  end

  def tag_name
    @tag_name ||= native.tag_name.downcase
  end
end

